# Color usage: teal vs terracotta

**Principle:** Teal is structure. Terracotta is meaning.

## Decision test (per element)
- Location / element type (label, eyebrow, section marker, nav, UI) → **teal**
- One phrase/number the reader should remember → **terracotta** (`.mark` or `--point`)
- Neither → **charcoal/ink**

## CSS classes
| Class | Use |
|---|---|
| `.label`, `.eyebrow`, `.mini-label` | Structural section markers (teal) |
| `.mark` | Rhetorical emphasis — max one per slide (terracotta) |
| `.stat__num--point` | When a single stat is the slide's deliberate point |
| `.card--point` | When one card is the featured takeaway |
| `.card` | Default structural card (teal left border) |

## Hard rules
1. Max one `.mark` per slide (guilt/objection grid is the exception: one `.mark` per card body).
2. Never color a label terracotta.
3. Teal label up top; terracotta `.mark` in content — not competing in the same block.
4. Default body text to ink/body tokens.
5. Stats in a set: identical ink unless one uses `--point`.

